855. opprimer‘ffi “surprise’‘; see 853 above. ambo ut necem ; the soldier would have been held guilty of murder according to the laws, cust-oms, and right both of Greece and Rome had he killed Mnesilochus, a free-born citizen, surprised with a meretrix, who was only a slave, and hired hythe former for a year. He had, of course, full control over her as long as he could show his right to her custody. His title, how- ever, does not appear to have been very clear, for she seems to be trying to get away from him. But he claims her as his wife, and the slave tries, and finally succeeds in making the old man believe this, who uses the word umore in v. 912, showing that he is fully convinced, whereas the slave and the soldier call her mulier, which may or may not have that meaning, and in fact it includes both, meretria· and umor. On this v. see n. vv. 22-3.
